Project Description

Project Inspired by Jenny Nova

In 2018, the New York Times published this article titled Detailed Maps Show How Neighborhoods Shape Children for Life. This article, years in the making, clearly demonstrated how some neighborhoods propel children to have better income than their parents’ while others shackle the children in poverty. This article was a powerful use of data to tell a compelling story for social change. In this workbook, we will reporduce a small subset of the NYT article by focusin on the San Jose county.

Data Skills

  • Data Wrangling
  • Data Visualization
  • Story Telling

Tools/Packages Used

  • Mapbox
  • Tidycensus
  • Stringr

Data

We will reverse engineer the necessary data by combining two publically available datasets: the census data (to get geographic information) and the Opportunity Atlas data (to get income information). Note, we will be studying the income mobility, or there lack of, of children born between 1978 and 1983 to families with the botton 25th percentile income.

Proceedure

Part I: Get Census Data

Tidycensus is a package that provides R users with access to the US national census. It has two major functions:

  1. get_decennial() which is used to access the 1990, 2000, and 2010 decennial US Census APIs, and
  2. get_acs(), which is used to access the 5-year American Community Survey APIs

For this project, we will focus on the get_acs() function. This function requires a few key arguments to return the desired dataset. The two that need explanation are:

  • geography: the specification of the US geographical designation for the desired data. See here to find the various options.
  • variables: There are over 22,000 variable IDs across different census files. We want to analyze the median household income in 2015. Hence, we will load the variables for 2015 from the acs5 file and search the resulting tibble for “Median Household Income.” This results in the code: B19013_001. See here for more detail.
vars <- load_variables(2015, "acs5", cache = TRUE)

Now we are ready to load the median income data for Santa Clara in 2015.

tract_boundaries <- 
  tidycensus::get_acs(
  geography = "tract",
  variables = "B19013_001",
  year = 2015,
  state = "CA",
  county = "Santa Clara",
  geometry = TRUE
)

Part II: Merge Census with Opportunity Atlas Data

Because we want to visually represent the income information on a map, and the income information is on the atlas dataset while the geographic information is on the census dataset, we want to join these two datasets.

income_with_boundaries <- 
  tract_boundaries %>% 
  left_join(san_jose_atlas_data, by = "GEOID")

Part III: Output the Data for Mapbox

Mapbox, the interactive visualizing platform, requires its input to be in a geojson format. Hence, we will write the above dataframe into a geojson.

income_with_boundaries %>% 
  write_sf(output_san_jose_atlas_census_data)
## Warning in CPL_write_ogr(obj, dsn, layer, driver,
## as.character(dataset_options), : GDAL Error 6: DeleteLayer() not supported by
## this dataset.

Part IV: Determine the Colors for Mapbox

We want to use the Red, Yellow, Blue color tone as used by the NYT article. First find all the possible colors

RColorBrewer::display.brewer.all()

Then choose the scheme that most resembles the NYT article.

RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(n = 11, "RdYlBu")
##  [1] "#A50026" "#D73027" "#F46D43" "#FDAE61" "#FEE090" "#FFFFBF" "#E0F3F8"
##  [8] "#ABD9E9" "#74ADD1" "#4575B4" "#313695"

We’ll now break the income data based on this breakdown based on percentages from 0 to 100% at every checkpoint at 10%s.

quantile(san_jose_atlas_data$kid_indiv_income, probs = seq(0, 1, 0.1))
##       0%      10%      20%      30%      40%      50%      60%      70% 
## 11536.97 24158.34 25877.84 27591.64 28449.55 30158.72 31015.54 31874.66 
##      80%      90%     100% 
## 33595.86 34462.61 46648.63

We will pass these these values to color Mapbox.

Conclusion

This map clearly demonstrates that children in significant parts of San Jose struggle with upward social mobility while others, situated closer to Silicon Valley, have the potential for upward economic mobility.

Next Steps:

This project could be further expanded to closely compare the children who achieved social mobility with those that struggled to do so in order to derive insights that could potentially inform economic policy in the county.
